		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cincinnati Ohio</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Novr 1848</date></p>
			<p>Revd Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Before I left <placeName>New York</placeName> on my return to this<lb/> city I wrote you a few lines&#44; under date of <date>31<hi rend="sup">st</hi> Augt.</date> by <persName>Mr. Abm.<lb/> Hart</persName> which you have no doubt received. Since my arrival&#44;<lb/> here I have had no communication from <persName>Mr. Noah</persName> on the subject<lb/> of the letter &#38;c I left with him for The Trustees of the <placeName>Crosby Street</placeName><lb/> Synagogue&#44; proposing a union of the congregations. I am writing<lb/> now urging him not to lose sight of this object. I notice<lb/> it has been adverted to and ably treated in the occident for last<lb/> month under the head &#8220;Association.&#8221; It is lamentable to witness<lb/> the apathy that prevails among us Jews while the world around<lb/> us is <sic>intensly</sic> engaged on subjects connected with the well&#45;being<lb/> of the human family&#59; surely this torpor cannot last&#59; the Jews<lb/> must go with the stream or incur the charge of being less alive<lb/> to the obligations imposed by their religion than any other people.<lb/> The proposed union is so manifestly calculated to produce most<lb/> important beneficial results as regard both the temporal and<lb/> spiritual condition of our Nation that I cannot abandon the<lb/> hope of soon seeing it carried into effect. Should the constituted<lb/> synagogue authorities decline acting upon the suggestion I<lb/> contemplate proposing to form an association for the same objects<lb/> to consist of private individuals of every congregation&#44; and shall<lb/> not hesitate to commence it if only a dozen influential gentlemen<lb/> filled with zeal for their faith and with a sincere desire to<lb/> witness its professors taking their proper position amidst the</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>nations among whom they have been dispersed for the holiest<lb/> and mightiest of purposes&#44; consent to join in it&#44; and I feel<lb/> persuaded that at no remote period after the formation of<lb/> such an association it will reckon among its members<lb/> almost every Israelite in these states. should your proposal<lb/> in the occident for ministers of the different synagogues<lb/> to meet in the ensuing spring be embraced by them generally<lb/> it may lead to important results. You are but an indiffer<lb/>&#45;ent correspondent yet I trust a reply to this will not be <sic>witheld</sic><lb/> by you&#44; and that I may anticipate your having success fully<lb/> used your kind endeavours to circulate the Retrospect&#8212;<lb/> as it will have the double purpose of serving me and<lb/> promoting the common cause.&#8212;Has <persName>Mr. Abm Hart</persName> got<lb/> a copy from you&#63; Had my time permitted of it I would<lb/> when at <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> have gone over with you the points<lb/> that work treats. You have it in your power to do much<lb/> towards calling attention to publications of this description<lb/> and I feel assured that whatever you can do towards aiding<lb/> such efforts will not be <sic>witheld</sic>&#44; especially as you are<lb/> well aware of the uphill work those have to encounter who<lb/> through the press attempt to rouse our people to action</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">As you have many opportunities of seeing <persName>Miss Gratz</persName><lb/> will you do me the favor to mention me respectfully to her<lb/> that when I left for her the letter entrusted to me by <persName>Mrs.<lb/> Etting</persName> I fully expected to have had the pleasure of waiting<lb/> upon her on my return to <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> from <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> &#38; regret exceedingly being deprived of doing so from the<lb/> necessity I was under of returning home by way of <placeName>Albany</placeName></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><placeName>Buffalo</placeName> &#38;c. It is however very probable that in the Spring<lb/> I shall assured visit <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> when I shall not fail<lb/> passing my respects to her.&#8212;excuse the liberty I am taking<lb/> but if I can in return serve you I shall be most happy<lb/> to do so I am reverend Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(6)">Your obt Servant</p>
          <p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">A A. Lindo</persName></p>
			<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
